[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] In the United Kingdom, the **Accession Council** is a ceremonial body which assembles in St James's Palace in London upon the death of a monarch to make formal proclamation of the accession of the successor to the throne.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] Under the terms of the Act of Settlement 1701, a new monarch succeeds automatically (demise of the Crown).
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] The proclamation confirms by name the identity of the new monarch, expresses loyalty to the "lawful and rightful Liege Lord", and formally announces the new monarch's regnal name, while the council witnesses the signing and sealing of several documents concerning the accession.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] The privy council (a subset of the accession council) is then called into the presence of the monarch to hear the monarch's address and the witness monarch's signing and sealing of documents.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] An Accession Council has confirmed every English (and later, British) monarch since James I in 1603.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] The members of the accession council are summoned to assemble at St.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] James's Palace and it meets outside the presence chamber of the monarch, where the presiding officer or clerk of the privy council reads out the proclamation, and it is signed by the accession council witnesses.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] Orders are made with respect to public readings of the proclamation.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] Only the privy council is then summoned to attend the monarch, and listen to the monarch's address; the monarch then signs several documents, and the documents are sealed.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] The two parts of the accession council meeting usually occur together, but if circumstances warrant may take place separately.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] The council's Proclamation of Accession, which confirms the name of the heir, is signed by all the attendant Privy Counsellors.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] Though proclamations have been worded broadly the same, they also vary as necessary.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] In the case of Victoria, certain words were included (having regard to section 2 of the Regency Act 1830 prescribing the Oath of Allegiance) which expressly reserved the rights of any child of the late king, William IV, which might be borne to his widow, Adelaide of Saxe-Meiningen.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] In the case of George VI, the proclamation was reworded because Edward VIII had abdicated, rather than died.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] The title "Emperor of India," assumed by Queen Victoria well into her reign, was added at the end of the list of titles at the proclamations of Edward VII, George V, Edward VIII and George VI, during whose reign that title was relinquished.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] In the case of Charles III, the proclamation was reworded to include the House of Commons for the first time.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] Long live the King!", of French royal origin, is not part of the official proclamation in the United Kingdom, contrary to popular belief.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] The proclamation has been ceremonially read out in various locations around the kingdom.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] By custom, it is usually first read from the Proclamation Gallery of Friary Court at St James's Palace by the heralds of the College of Arms.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] Other readings in London have historically followed, concluding at the Royal Exchange in the presence of the Lord Mayor of London.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] Local proclamation events then occur, such as one at the original location of Mercat Cross in Edinburgh by the heralds of the Court of the Lord Lyon.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] In 2022, the first reading at the palace was televised live, and other readings in London were omitted except for the one at the Exchange.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] Under the Acts of Union 1707, monarchs are required upon succeeding to the throne to make an oath to "maintain and preserve" the Church of Scotland.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] This oath is normally made at the Accession Council.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] Once the monarch makes a sacred oath to the council, the Garter Principal King of Arms steps onto the Proclamation Gallery which overlooks Friary Court to proclaim the new monarch.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] Queen Elizabeth II was in Kenya when she acceded to the throne, and the Accession Council therefore met twice, first for the proclamation and again so that the new Queen could take the oath.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] Upon accession, a new sovereign is also required to make what is known as the Accession Declaration.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] This is not usually made at a meeting of the Accession Council but in the presence of Parliament on the first State Opening following the monarch's accession to the throne or at their coronation, whichever occurs first.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] King George VI made the declaration at his coronation.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-council] The following is a list of the dates of accession councils and the public reading of proclamations.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-declaration-act-1910] The **Accession Declaration Act 1910** is an Act which was passed by the Parliament of the United Kingdom to alter the declaration that the Sovereign is required to make at their accession to the throne as first required by the Bill of Rights 1689.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-declaration-act-1910] In it, they solemnly declare themself to be faithful to the Protestant faith.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-declaration-act-1910] This declaration differs from the original one in that it places emphasis on the sovereign being a Protestant, whereas the previous wording placed emphasis on denunciation of Catholicism.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-declaration-act-1910] The declaration is usually made either at the opening of the first parliament of the new monarch's reign (i.e. during the State Opening of Parliament) or if earlier, as in the cases of George VI and Charles III, at their coronation.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-declaration-act-1910] The Bill of Rights of 1689 required, among other things, that any monarch succeeding to the throne take the declaration as laid out by the Test Act 1678; Reiterated by section 2 of the Act of Settlement 1701.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-declaration-act-1910] The declaration, in that form, was originally administered under the Test Acts to all civil and military officials of the Crown, including the monarch him/herself (starting with William III and Mary II).
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-declaration-act-1910] Following Catholic emancipation, the law was changed to require only the monarch (who remained Supreme Head of the Church of England) to take the oath.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-declaration-act-1910] However, when Edward VII took the throne, he was unhappy at the pointedly anti-Catholic wording of the oath (viewing it as outdated and unnecessarily offensive to Catholics, of whom he had several in his private social circle), and wished to have it changed before the next succession.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-declaration-act-1910] When he died in 1910, his successor, George V, who agreed with his father's sentiments, made it known that he would refuse to open parliament as long as he was obliged to make the declaration in its then-current form.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/accession-declaration-act-1910] Asquith agreed with the King, and the Act was passed through the then-sitting parliament before the new King was required to open the new parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-adjournal] An **Act of Adjournal** is secondary legislation made by the High Court of Justiciary, the supreme criminal court of Scotland, to regulate the proceedings of Scottish courts hearing criminal matters.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-adjournal] Now primarily derived from the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995, the original power to create Acts of Adjournal is derived from an Act of the Parliament of Scotland in 1672.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-adjournal] Before promulgation, Acts of Adjournal are reviewed and may be commented upon by the Criminal Courts Rules Council.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-adjournal] Following Scottish devolution and the establishment of the Scottish Parliament, Acts of Adjournal are made as Scottish Statutory Instruments.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-adjournal] Before devolution, acts were made as United Kingdom statutory instruments.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-adjournal] 40) (originally *Act concerning the regulation of the judicatories*) created the High Court of Justiciary by attaching five Lords of Session to the Lord Justice General and Lord Justice Clerk.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-adjournal] The act provided that "the judges of that court [...] regulate the inferior officers thereof, and order every other thing concerning the said court," a provision which remains in force and which created the distinction between Acts of Adjournal and Acts of Sederunt.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-adjournal] In the 19th century, a reforming of the High Court of Justiciary made all Lords of Session *ex officio* Lords Commissioners of Justiciary.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-adjournal] That reformation, while now repealed, is replicated by the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995, which further provides that the Lord President of the Court of Session is to hold the office of Lord Justice General.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] An **act of Parliament** in the United Kingdom is primary legislation passed by the UK Parliament in Westminster, London.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] An act of Parliament can be enforced in all four of the UK constituent countries (England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland).
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] As a result of devolution the majority of acts that are passed by Parliament increasingly only apply either to England and Wales only, or England only.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Generally only acts relating to constitutional and reserved matters now apply to the whole of the United Kingdom.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A draft piece of legislation is called a bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] When this is passed by Parliament and given royal assent, it becomes an act and part of statute law.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A bill and an act of Parliament typically include a short title and a long title, a number of clauses and, in many cases, one or more **schedules**.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Acts of Parliament are classified as either "public general acts" or "local and personal acts" (also known as "private acts").
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Bills are also classified as "public", "private", or "hybrid".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Public general acts form the largest category of legislation, in principle affecting the public general law applying to everyone across the entire United Kingdom, or at least to one or more of its constituent countries of England, Northern Ireland, Scotland, or Wales.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Most public general acts proceed through Parliament as a public bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Occasionally, a bill is treated as hybrid.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Private acts are either local or personal in their effect, applying to a specifically named locality or legal person in a manner different from all others.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Private bills are "usually promoted by organisations, like local authorities or private companies, to give themselves powers beyond, or in conflict with, the general law.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Private bills only change the law as it applies to specific individuals or organisations, rather than the general public.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] They include acts to confer powers on certain local authorities, an example from 2008 being the Canterbury City Council Bill, which makes provisions relating to street trading and consumer protection in the city.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Private bills can also affect certain companies: the Northern Bank Bill allowed the statutory right of Northern Bank to issue bank notes to be transferred to Danske Bank which had acquired it.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Other private bills may affect particular companies established by act of Parliament such as TSB Bank and Transas.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Personal acts are a sub-category of private acts, which confer specific rights or duties on a named individual or individuals, for example allowing two persons to marry even though they are within a "prohibited degree of consanguinity or affinity" such as stepfather and stepdaughter.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Private bills, common in the 19th century, are now rare, as new planning legislation introduced in the 1960s removed the need for many of them.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Only a few, if any, are passed each year.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Parliamentary authorities maintain a list of all private bills before parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Hybrid bills combine elements of both public and private bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] While they propose to make changes to the general law, they also contain provisions applying to specific individuals or bodies.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Once passed, hybrid bills are printed as part of the public general acts.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Parliamentary authorities maintain a list of all hybrid bills before parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] It is important not to confuse private bills with private members' bills, which are public bills intended to effect a general change in the law.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The only difference from other public bills is that they are brought forward by a private member (a backbencher) rather than by the government.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Twenty private members' bills per session are allowed to be introduced, with the sponsoring private members selected by a ballot of the whole house, and additional bills may be introduced under the Ten Minute Rule.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Financial bills raise revenue and authorise how money is spent.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The best-known such bills are the normally annual Finance Bills introduced by the Chancellor of the Exchequer in the Budget.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] This usually encompasses all the changes to be made to tax law for the year.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Its formal description is "a Bill to grant certain duties, to alter other duties, and to amend the law relating to the National Debt and the Public Revenue, and to make further provision in connection with finance".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Consolidated Fund and Appropriation Bills authorise government spending.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] This type of bill is designed to keep the business of government and public affairs up to date.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] These bills may not be substantial or controversial in party political terms.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Two sub-classes of the housekeeping bill are *consolidation bills*, which set out existing law in a clearer and more up-to-date form without changing its substance; and the tax law rewrite bills, which do the same for tax law.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] An act of Parliament will often confer power on the King in Council, a minister, or another public body to create delegated legislation, usually by means of a statutory instrument.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Bills may start their passage in either the House of Commons or House of Lords, although bills which are mainly or entirely financial will start in the Commons.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Although not strictly part of the legislative process, a period of consultation will take place before a bill is drafted.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Within government, the Treasury and other departments with an interest will be consulted along with the devolved administrations in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Outside government, interested parties such as trade unions, industry bodies and pressure groups will be asked for their views on any proposals.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The Cabinet Office Code of Practice specifies a minimum consultation period of twelve weeks.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Consultation documents are widely circulated (see for example the Home Office consultation on extreme pornography and the Scottish Government's consultation on food policy).
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The character of the consultation is shaped by the government's determination to press forward with a particular set of proposals.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A government may publish a green paper outlining various legislative options or a white paper, which is a clear statement of intent.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] It is increasingly common for a small number of government bills to be published in draft before they are presented in Parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] These bills are then considered either by the relevant select committee of the House of Commons or by an ad hoc joint committee of both Houses.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] This provides an opportunity for the committee to express a view on the bill and propose amendments before it is introduced.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] With increased time for scrutiny backed up with considered evidence, draft bills may present governments with difficulty in getting their way.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The sponsoring government department will then write to the relevant policy committee of the Cabinet.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The proposals are only discussed at a meeting if disagreements arise.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Even an uncontroversial proposal may face administrative hurdles.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A potential change in the law may have to wait for a more extensive bill in that policy area to be brought forward before it is worthwhile devoting parliamentary time to it.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The proposal will then be bundled together with more substantive measures in the same Bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The Ministerial Committee on the Legislative Programme (LP), including the leaders and government chief whips in both houses, is responsible for the timetable of legislation.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] This committee decides which house a bill will start in, recommends to the Cabinet which proposals will be in the King's Speech, which will be published in draft and how much parliamentary time will be required.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Following a process of consultation, the sponsoring department will send drafting instructions to parliamentary counsel, expert lawyers working for the government responsible for writing legislation.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] These instructions will describe what the bill should do but not the detail of how this is achieved.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The parliamentary counsel must draft the legislation clearly to minimise the possibility of legal challenge and to fit the bill in with existing UK, European Union and delegated legislation.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A finished bill must be approved or scrutinised by the sponsoring department and minister, parliamentary counsel and LP.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The final stage is the submission of the bill to the authorities of the House in which it is to start its legislative journey.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] In the Commons, this is the Clerk of Legislation; in the Lords it is the Public Bill Office.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] After this process, the bill is then ready for introduction.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The first reading is a formality and no debate or vote occurs.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A notice that a bill is being presented for its first reading appears on the Order Paper for that day.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] As we can see in this video footage of the first reading, the MP is called by the Speaker at the commencement of public business and brings a 'dummy bill', a sheet of paper with the short and long titles and the names of up to twelve supporters, to the Clerk of the House at the Table.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The Clerk reads out the short title and the Speaker says "Second reading what day?" For all government bills, the response is almost always "tomorrow", or the next sitting day.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A date is also set for private members bills.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The decision for scheduling such bills is crucial as they are not given 'government time' to be debated.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The bill is recorded in the proceedings as having been read for a first time, having been ordered to be printed and to be read a second time on a particular date.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] In the case of a government bill, Explanatory Notes, which try to explain the effect of the bill in simple language, are also usually ordered to be printed.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A bill introduced in this way is known as a *presentation bill*.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Bills can also be introduced in the Commons by being brought in from the Lords, being *brought in by resolution* (like the Finance Bill) or when an MP gets leave to bring in a *ten-minute rule bill*.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A government bill can be introduced first into either House.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Bills which begin in the Lords have '[Lords]' suffixed to its title when in the Lords and '[HL]' when in the Commons.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Bills which deal primarily with taxation or public expenditure begin their passage in the Commons since the financial privileges of that House mean that it has primacy in these matters (see Parliament Acts 1911 and 1949).
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Conversely, bills relating to the judicial system, Law Commission bills and consolidation bills begin their passage in the House of Lords which by convention has primacy in these matters.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] In the second reading, which in theory is supposed to occur two weekends after the first reading, a debate on the general principles of the bill is followed by a vote.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] This is the main opportunity to debate the principle of the bill rather than individual clauses.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A division at this stage, therefore, represents a direct challenge to the principle of the bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] If the bill is read a second time, it proceeds to the committee stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Normally, the Second Reading of a Government bill is approved.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A defeat for a Government bill on this Reading usually signifies a major loss.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The last time this happened was at the second reading of the Shops Bill for the government of Margaret Thatcher in 1986.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The bill, which liberalised controls on Sunday trading, was defeated in the Commons by 14 votes.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Second reading debates on government bills usually take a day, in practice about six hours.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Smaller and less controversial bills will receive less time and wholly uncontroversial measures will receive a second reading 'on the nod' with no debate whatsoever.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] As we can see from video footage of the debate for this bill, second readings of government bills take place on a motion moved (for Government bills) by a minister in the department responsible for the legislation "that the bill now be read a second time".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The minister outlines the overall purpose of the Bill and highlights particular parts of the Bill they consider most important.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The official Opposition spokesperson responds with their views on the Bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The debate continues with other Opposition parties and backbench MPs giving their opinions on the principles of the Bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The minister will eventually bring the debate to a conclusion by saying, of the bill, "I commend it to the House".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The Speaker will then *put the question* by saying, for example, "The Question is, that the Bill be now read a second time".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The Speaker then invites supporters of the bill to say "aye" and then opponents say "no": first he says, "All members of that opinion say 'aye'", and supporters say 'aye'; then the speaker says "contrary 'no'", and opponents say 'no'.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] In what is known as *collecting the voices* the Speaker makes a judgement as to the loudest cry.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A clear majority, either way, will prompt the response "I think the Ayes/Noes have it".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] This can be forced to a division by continued cries either way.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] If the result is at all in doubt, a division will be called and the Speaker will say "Division.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] This refers not to the division lobbies used for voting, but the Members' Lobby beyond the chamber which is cleared by the doorkeepers.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] At this point, division bells will ring throughout the palace and also in nearby flats, pubs and restaurants whose owners pay to be connected to the system.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] This allows MPs who may not be in the debate to come and vote on the issue in question.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] After two minutes, the Speaker will *put the Question again* to assess whether there is still disagreement.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] He will then name the tellers, whose job it is to count the votes.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] These will usually be government and opposition whips.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] In the example we have looked at: "Tellers for the Ayes Mr.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] If no teller has come forward, or only one, the Speaker declares the result for the other side.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] One teller from each side goes to the end of each division lobby and they count MPs as they emerge.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Whips are also at the other end of the lobby to try to ensure that their MPs vote with the party line.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The names are taken by division clerks and are published in Hansard the next day (see example from Hansard or with greater clarity from the Public Whip).
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Eight minutes after first calling the division, the Speaker says "lock the doors".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The doorkeepers lock the doors leading into the lobbies and no more MPs can get in to vote.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] When every member has passed the division clerks and tellers, a *division slip* is produced by the Clerks at the Table and is given to one of the tellers on the winning side.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The tellers then form up at the Table in front of the Mace facing the Speaker, and the teller with the slip reads the result to the House, for example: "The Ayes to the right, 291.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The Clerk then takes the slip to the Speaker, who repeats the result and adds "So the Ayes have it, the Ayes have it.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Unlock." The doorkeepers then unlock the doors to the division lobbies.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Divisions on second readings can be on a straight opposition or a vote on a 'reasoned amendment', detailing the reasons the bill's opponents do not want it read a second time, which may be selected by the Speaker.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Bills defeated at a second reading cannot progress further or be reintroduced with exactly the same wording in the same session.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] In the case of Government Bills, the House normally passes forthwith (i.e. without debate but almost always with a vote) a Programme Order in the form of a *programme motion*, setting out the timetable for the committee and remaining stages of the Bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] This takes place immediately after the second reading.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The House may also pass a separate *money resolution*, authorising any expenditure arising from the Bill; and/or a *ways and means resolution*, authorising any new taxes or charges the Bill creates.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Bills are not programmed in the House of Lords.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] This usually takes place in a standing committee in the Commons and on the floor of the House in the Lords.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The committee considers each clause of the bill and may make amendments to it.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Significant amendments may be made at committee stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] In some cases, whole groups of clauses are inserted or removed.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The report state, known formally as "consideration", takes place on the Floor of the House, and is a further opportunity to amend the bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Unlike committee stage, the House need not consider every clause of the bill, only those to which amendments have been tabled.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] In the third reading, a debate on the final text of the bill, as amended.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] In the Lords, further amendments may be made on third reading, in the Commons, it is usually a short debate followed by a single vote.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Lords, if it originated in the Commons; to the Commons if it is a Lords bill), which may amend it.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The Commons may reject a bill from the Lords outright.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The Lords may amend a bill from the Commons but, if they reject it, the Commons may force it through without the Lords' consent in the following Session of Parliament, as is detailed below.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The Lords can neither initiate nor amend money bills, bills dealing exclusively with public expenditure or the raising of revenue.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Whether a bill is a money bill is decided by the Speaker of the House of Commons.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] If the other House amends the bill, the bill and amendments are sent back for a further stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] There is a constitutional convention that the House of Lords should not spend more than 60 days over bills sent to them by the Commons.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Under the Parliament Acts 1911 and 1949, which do not apply for bills seeking to extend Parliament's length to more than five years, if the Lords reject a bill originated in the House of Commons, then the Commons may pass that bill again in the next session.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The bill is then submitted for royal assent even though the Lords did not pass it.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] If the Lords do not approve of a money bill within thirty days of passage in the Commons, the bill is submitted for royal assent nevertheless.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] It may agree to them, amend them, propose other amendments in lieu or reject them.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] A bill may pass backwards and forwards several times at this stage, as each House amends or rejects changes proposed by the other, a process referred to colloquially as parliamentary ping-pong.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] If each House insists on disagreeing with the other, the bill is lost under the 'double insistence' rule, unless avoiding action is taken.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] As a result of devolution, the Senedd, the Northern Ireland Assembly, and the Scottish Parliament are also able to create primary legislation for their respective devolved institutions.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] These devolved legislatures are able to create legislation regarding all but reserved and excepted matters.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] However, acts of the Parliament of the United Kingdom remain supreme and can overrule the devolved legislatures.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] By convention, the Parliament of the United Kingdom does not normally do this without a legislative consent motion.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] In the United Kingdom, Parliament is sovereign, so it is not bound by a constitution or judicial review.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] This implied repeal thinking is later mentioned in *R (HS2 Action Alliance Ltd) v Secretary of State for Transport*, in relation to two "constitutional" statutes.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] It was said that "Acts of Parliament are no longer sovereign but can be overruled if they are incompatible with European Laws", as was the case in *Thoburn*.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] However, by virtue of express repeal in the European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018, the UK has now left the European Union and this ceased to be the case when the Brexit transition period ended, on 31 December 2020.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Parliament has also devolved significant powers to the Northern Ireland Assembly, Scottish Parliament and Senedd Cymru.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Because of its sovereignty, it is free to overrule or even abolish these institutions (a recent instance when it did was the Northern Ireland (Executive Formation etc) Act 2019).
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] However, this is unlikely in practice, in part because of the Sewel convention, a constitutional convention, which is now partly statutorised.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Secondary legislation, otherwise known as delegated legislation, are devolved powers, primarily given to ministers.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] International treaties are not ratified in the UK until a minister has laid a copy of the treaty before Parliament and 21 sitting days have passed without either House resolving that the treaty should not be ratified.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] At the end of a medieval Parliament of England, a collection of acts of a public character was made in the form of a Statute Roll and given the title of the king's regnal year.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Each particular act formed a section, or a chapter, of the complete statute, so that, e.g. the Vagabonds Act 1383 became 7 Ric.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Enrolment of public acts on manuscript parchment "Parliament Rolls" continued until 1850.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The longest act of Parliament in the form of a scroll is an act regarding taxation passed in 1821.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] It is nearly a quarter of a mile (348 m) long, and used to take two men a whole day to rewind.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Until 1850, a paper draft was brought into the house in which the bill started.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] After the committee stage, the bill was inscribed on a parchment roll and this parchment was then passed to the other house which could introduce amendments.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Knives were used to scrape away the script from the top surface of the rolls before the new text was added.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Since 1850, two copies of each act were printed on vellum, one for preservation in the House of Lords and the other for transmission to the Public Record Office.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Since 1887 annual volumes of public acts ("Statute Books") have been printed.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] In these volumes, public acts but also some private acts and various "Local and Personal Acts declared Public" have been included.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] All UK acts of Parliament since 1497 are kept in the House of Lords Record Office; the oldest act in that collection is the "Taking of Apprentices for Worsteads in the County of Norfolk" Act 1496 (12 Hen.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] 1), a reference to the wool worsted manufacture at Worstead in Norfolk, England.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Acts passed before 1 January 1963 are cited by session and chapter.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The session of Parliament in which the act was passed is referred to by the regnal year or years of the reigning Monarch and his name, which is usually abbreviated.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] All acts passed on or after 1 January 1963 are cited by calendar year and chapter.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] All recent acts have a short title, or citation (e.g.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Local Government Act 2003, National Health Service Act 1974).
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The Short Titles Act 1896 retrospectively gave short titles to most old statutes that were still live.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] Many acts of a private, personal or local character often have not ever been printed, surviving only in a single manuscript copy in the Victoria Tower.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The UK's Ministry of Justice publishes most acts of Parliament in an online statute law database.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] It is the official revised edition of the primary legislation of the United Kingdom.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament-united-kingdom] The database shows acts as amended by subsequent legislation and is the statute book of UK legislation.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] An **act of parliament**, as a form of primary legislation, is a text of law passed by the legislative body of a jurisdiction (often a parliament or council).
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In most countries with a parliamentary system of government, acts of parliament begin as a bill, which the legislature votes on.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Depending on the structure of government, this text may then be subject to assent or approval from the executive branch.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] A draft act of parliament is known as a bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In other words, a bill is a proposed law that needs to be discussed in the parliament before it can become a law.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In territories with a Westminster system, most bills that have any possibility of becoming law are introduced into parliament by the government.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] This will usually happen following the publication of a "white paper", setting out the issues and the way in which the proposed new law is intended to deal with them.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] A bill may also be introduced into parliament without formal government backing; this is known as a private member's bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In territories with a multicameral parliament, most bills may be first introduced in any chamber.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] However, certain types of legislation are required, either by constitutional convention or by law, to be introduced into a specific chamber.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] For example, bills imposing a tax, or involving public expenditure, are introduced into the House of Commons in the United Kingdom, Canada's House of Commons, Lok Sabha of India and Ireland's Dáil as a matter of law.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Conversely, bills proposed by the Law Commission and consolidation bills traditionally start in the House of Lords.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Once introduced, a bill must go through a number of stages before it can become law.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In theory, this allows the bill's provisions to be debated in detail, and for amendments to the original bill to also be introduced, debated, and agreed to.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In bicameral parliaments, a bill that has been approved by the chamber into which it was introduced then sends the bill to the other chamber.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Broadly speaking, each chamber must separately agree to the same version of the bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Finally, the approved bill receives assent; in most territories this is merely a formality and is often a function exercised by the head of state.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In some countries, such as in France, Belgium, Luxembourg, Spain and Portugal, the term for a bill differs depending on whether it is initiated by the government (when it is known as a "draft"), or by the parliament (a "proposition", i.e., a private member's bill).
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Second reading: As in the UK, the stage involves a debate on the general principles of the bill and is followed by a vote.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Again, the second reading of a government bill is usually approved.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] A defeat for a government bill on this reading signifies a major loss.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Consideration in detail: This usually takes place on the floor of the House.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Generally, committees sit on the floor of the House and consider the bill in detail.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Third reading: A debate on the final text of the bill, as amended.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Very rarely do debates occur during this stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Passage: The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Senate, if it originated in the House of Representatives; to the House of Representatives, if it is a Senate bill), which may amend it.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If the other House amends the bill, the bill and amendments are posted back to the original House for a further stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The State of Queensland's Parliament is unicameral and skips this and the rest of the stages.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Consideration of Senate/Representatives amendments: The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] It may agree to them, amend them, propose other amendments in lieu, or reject them.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] However, the Senate may not amend money bills, though it can "request" the House to make amendments.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] A bill may pass backward and forward several times at this stage, as each House amends or rejects changes proposed by the other.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If each House insists on disagreeing with the other, the bill is lost.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Disagreement between the Houses: Often, when a bill cannot be passed in the same form by both Houses, it is "laid aside", i.e. abandoned.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In the federal Parliament, there is also a special constitutional procedure allowing the passage of the bill without the separate agreement of both houses.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If the House twice passes the same bill, and the Senate twice fails to pass that bill (either through rejection or through the passage of unacceptable amendments), then the Governor-General may dissolve both Houses of Parliament simultaneously and call an election for the entire Parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] After the election, if the House again passes the bill, but the deadlock between the Houses persists, then the Governor-General may convene a joint sitting of both Houses, where a final decision will be taken on the bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Although the House and the Senate sit as a single body, bills passed at a joint sitting are treated as if they had been passed by each chamber separately.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The procedure only applies if the bill originated in the House of Representatives.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Six double dissolutions have occurred, though a joint sitting was only held once, in 1974.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The bill is sent to the viceroy (the Governor-General for the Commonwealth; the governor for a state; the administrator for a territory) for royal assent.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Acts in the Australian Capital Territory do not require this step.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Second reading: This stage involves a debate on the general principles of the bill and is followed by a vote.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The second reading of a government bill is usually approved.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If the bill is read a second time, then it progresses to the committee stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Committee stage: This usually takes place in a standing committee of the Commons or Senate.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Report stage: this takes place on the floor of the appropriate chamber, and allows the House or Senate to approve amendments made in committee, or to propose new ones.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Passage: The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Senate, if it originated in the House of Commons; to the Commons, if it is a Senate bill), where it will face a virtually identical process.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If the other House amends the bill, the bill and amendments are sent back to the original House for a further stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Consideration of Senate/Commons amendments: The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Disagreement between the Houses: There is no specific procedure to resolve a dispute between the houses.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Either house can amend or reject a bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The debate on each stage is actually debate on a specific motion.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] For the first reading, there is no debate.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In the Report stage, the debate is on the motions for specific amendments.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Once a bill has passed both Houses in an identical form, it is presented to the Governor General, who gives it royal assent.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Although the Governor General can refuse to assent a bill, this power has never been exercised.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Bills being reviewed by Parliament are assigned numbers: 2 to 200 for government bills, 201 to 1000 for private member's bills, and 1001 up for private bills.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] They are preceded by C- if they originate in the House of Commons, or S- if they originate in the Senate.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] For example, Bill C-250 was a private member's bill introduced in the House.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Bills C-1 and S-1 are pro forma bills, and are introduced at the beginning of each session in order to assert the right of each Chamber to manage its own affairs.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] They are introduced and read a first time, and then are dropped from the Order Paper.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Second reading – discussion stage: This stage consists of detailed consideration of the bill and proposed amendments.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Third reading – voting stage: This stage is confined only to arguments either in support of the bill or for its rejection as a whole, without referring to its details.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] After the bill is passed, it is sent to the other house.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Bill in the other house (Rajya Sabha): After a bill, other than a money bill, is transmitted to the other house, it goes through all the stages in that house as that in the first house.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] But if the bill passed by one house is amended by the other house, it goes back to the originating house.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] President's approval: When a bill is passed by both the houses, it is sent to the President for his approval.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The President can assent or withhold his assent to a bill or he can return a bill, other than a money bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If the President gives his assent, the bill is published in *The Gazette of India* and becomes an Act from the date of his assent.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If he withholds his assent, the bill is dropped, which is known as pocket veto.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The pocket veto is not written in the constitution and has only been exercised once, by President Zail Singh in 1986, over the postal act where the government wanted to open postal letters without warrant.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If the president returns it for reconsideration, the Parliament must do so, but if it is passed again and returned to him, he must give his assent to it.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In the Irish Parliament, the Oireachtas, bills pass through the following stages.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Bills may be initiated in either the Dáil or the Seanad, and must pass both houses.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Second stage – this involves a discussion of the general principle of the bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] It is introduced by the sponsoring minister (or in the case of a private member's bill, by the member) and is followed by contributions from the floor of the house.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Finally, the debate is brought to a conclusion by voting on the proposal "that the bill now be read a second time".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Third stage, commonly referred to as the Committee Stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] This involves section by section scrutiny of the bill and any amendments which have been tabled.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In the Dáil this usually takes place in a committee room and will involve examination by one of the select committees.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In the Seanad, this stage takes place in the chamber.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The Seanad may only make recommendations rather than amendments, in the case of a money bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Fourth stage, commonly referred to as the Report Stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] At this point, a version of the bill incorporating any changes made at the Committee Stage is printed for consideration.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In both houses, this stage is taken on the floor of the chamber.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Amendments may be considered at this stage but must arise from matters discussed or changes made at the Committee Stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Fifth stage: in practice this is a formality, taken with the fourth stage and referred to as the Report and Final Stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Passage in the other house: the same stages are repeated in the other house and the bill is then deemed to have been passed, except that any bill initiated in the Dáil and amended by the Seanad must return to the Dáil for final consideration.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Signature: once the bill has passed both houses it is sent to the President for signature.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The signed copy is then enrolled in the Office of the Supreme Court.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Select committee stage: The bill is considered by a select committee, which scrutinises the bill in detail and hears public submissions on the matter.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The select committee may recommend amendments to the bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Second reading: The general principles of the bill are debated, and a vote is held.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If the bill is approved, it is put before a Committee of the House.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Committee of the House: The bill is debated and voted on, clause by clause, by the whole House sitting as a committee.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Third reading: Summarising arguments are made, and a final vote is taken.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If the bill is approved, it is passed to the Governor-General for royal assent.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] New Zealand has no upper house, and so no further approval is necessary.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] A draft piece of legislation is called a *bill*; when this is passed by Parliament it becomes an *act* and part of statute law.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] There are two types of bill and act, *public* and *private*.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Public acts apply to the whole of the UK or a number of its constituent countries – England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Private acts are local and personal in their effect, giving special powers to bodies such as local authorities or making exceptions to the law in particular geographic areas.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] First reading: This is a formality; no vote occurs.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The bill is presented and ordered to be printed and, in the case of private members' bills, a date is set for second reading.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Second reading: A debate on the general principles of the bill is followed by a vote.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Committee stage: This usually takes place in a public bill committee in the Commons and on the floor of the House in the Lords.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The committee considers each clause of the bill, and may make amendments to it.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Consideration (or report) stage: This takes place on the floor of the House, and is a further opportunity to amend the bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Third reading: A debate on the final text of the bill, as amended in the House of Lords.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Further amendments may be tabled at this stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Passage: The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Lords, if it originated in the Commons; to the Commons, if it is a Lords bill), which may amend it.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Consideration of Lords/Commons amendments: The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Royal assent: the bill is passed with any amendments and becomes an act of Parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Stage one: The bill is considered by one or more of the subject committees of the parliament, which normally take evidence from the bill's promoter and other interested parties before reporting to the parliament on the principles of the bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Other committees, notably the Finance and Subordinate Legislation Committees, may also feed in at this stage.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The report from the committee is followed by a debate in the full parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Stage two: The bill returns to the subject committee where it is subject to line-by-line scrutiny and amendment.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] This is similar to the committee stage in the UK Parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Stage three: The bill as amended by the committee returns to the full parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] There is a further opportunity for amendment, followed by a debate on the whole bill, at the end of which the parliament decides whether to pass the bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Royal assent: After the bill has been passed, the presiding officer submits it to the monarch for royal assent.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] However, he cannot do so until a four-week period has elapsed during which the law officers of the Scottish government or the UK government can refer the bill to the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom for a ruling on whether it is within the powers of the parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] There are special procedures for emergency bills, member's bills (similar to private member's bills in the UK Parliament), committee bills, and private bills.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In Singapore, the bill passes through these certain stages before becoming into an Act of Parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Second reading: In this stage, the bill is further discussed and put to a second vote.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If more than half of the votes are ayes the bill proceeds to the select committee.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Select committee: The select committee consists of people not only from the parliaments, but also the people who could be affected by the bill is passed into law.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] This is to ensure equality and that the bill is fair for all.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If the bill is in favour, it will proceed to the third reading.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Third reading: After the select committee has discussed and are in favour of the bill, they will put it to a vote.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] At this juncture, if the votes are more than half ayes, it will be sent to the President of Singapore.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] President Assent: The president must give permission in order for the bill to be passed.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] If they approve it, it will become a statute passed down by the members of parliament which is called an Act of Parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Acts passed by the Parliament of England did not originally have titles, and could only be formally cited by reference to the parliamentary session in which they were passed, with each individual act being identified by year and chapter number.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Descriptive titles began to be added to the enrolled acts by the official clerks, as a reference aid; over time, titles came to be included within the text of each bill.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Since the mid-nineteenth century, it has also become common practice for acts to have a short title, as a convenient alternative to the sometimes lengthy main titles.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The Short Titles Act 1892, and its replacement the Short Titles Act 1896, gave short titles to many acts which previously lacked them.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The numerical citation of acts has also changed over time.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The original method was based on the regnal year (or years) in which the relevant parliamentary session met.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] This has been replaced in most territories by simple reference to the calendar year, with the first act passed being chapter 1, and so on.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] In the United Kingdom, legislation has referenced by year and chapter number since 1963 (Acts of Parliament Numbering and Citation Act 1962).
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Each act is numbered consecutively based on the date it received royal assent, for example the 43rd act passed in 1980 would be 1980 chapter 43.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] The full reference includes the (short) title and would be the Magistrate's Court Act 1980 (c.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-parliament] Until the 1980s, acts of the Australian state of Victoria were numbered in a continuous sequence from 1857; thus the Age of Majority Act 1977 was No.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] An **Act of Sederunt** (/səˈdɛrənt/ *sə-DERR-ənt*; meaning a meeting or sitting of a court) is secondary legislation made by the Court of Session, the supreme civil court of Scotland, to regulate the proceedings of Scottish courts and tribunals hearing civil matters.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] Originally made under an Act of the Parliament of Scotland of 1532, the modern power to make Acts of Sederunt is largely derived from the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] Since 2013, draft Acts have also been prepared by the Scottish Civil Justice Council and submitted to the Court of Session for approval.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] Following Scottish devolution and the establishment of the Scottish Parliament, Acts of Sederunt are made as Scottish statutory instruments.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] Previously, Acts were made as United Kingdom statutory instruments, and before that were a separate class of legislation.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session—more accurately the College of Justice—was established by the Parliament of Scotland under James V in 1532.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The act of Parliament establishing the Court, later named the College of Justice Act 1532 (c.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] Although established in 1532, it was not until the passing of the **College of Justice Act 1540** (March c.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] 10 (S)), also known as the Act of Sederunt 1540 (originally titled *Ratification of the institution of the college of justice*) that the Court of Session gained the power to make law through Acts of Sederunt.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The Courts Act 1672 (originally *Act concerning the regulation of the judicatories*) created the High Court of Justiciary, the supreme criminal court of Scotland, by attaching five of the Lords of Session to the Lord Justice General and Lord Justice Clerk.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The Courts Act also provided that "the judges of that court ... regulate the inferior officers thereof, and order every other thing concerning the said court", and so created the distinction between Acts of Sederunt and Acts of Adjournal which continues to exist to this day.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] Following a 19th-century reforming of the High Court of Justiciary, all Lords of Session were *ex officio* Lords Commissioners of Justiciary, instead of the original five ordained by the Courts Act.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] Although that reformation was repealed, its effect was replicated by the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995, which provided that the Lord President of the Court of Session was also to hold the office of Lord Justice General.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The powers of the Court of Session to make Acts of Sederunt were partially consolidated by the Administration of Justice (Scotland) Act 1933, which also made significant changes to the structure and operations of the Court.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] One of these significant changes was the establishing of a Rules Council, composed of the Lord President as well as Court of Session judges and practising lawyers, to propose Acts of Sederunt to the Court.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The Act also created a Sheriff Court Rules Council, to carry out the same functions but in relation to the sheriff courts.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The Sheriff Courts (Scotland) Act 1971 enabled the Court of Session to regulate the sheriff courts and Sheriff Appeal Court when they heard civil matters.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The Act also dissolved the Sheriff Court Rules Council created by the Administration of Justice (Scotland) Act 1933, and created a new Sheriff Court Rules Council to continually review sheriff court procedure and submit to the Court of Session draft Acts of Sederunt for regulating sheriff courts.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session Act 1988 was another consolidating act, now with sections relating to Acts of Sederunt largely repealed or modified by the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014, that also altered the structure of the Court of Session.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The remaining powers to make Acts of Sederunt relate to summary trials—although the actual power is now derived from the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014—and the considering of applications to appeal to the Inner House by a single judge.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session Rules Council and Sheriff Court Rules Council were dissolved by the Scottish Civil Justice Council and Criminal Legal Assistance Act 2013, which established the Scottish Civil Justice Council as their replacement.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] (Scotland) Act 2016 to include draft inquiry procedure rules.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session's power to create Acts of Sederunt was extended by the Inquiries into Fatal Accidents and Sudden Deaths etc.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] (Scotland) Act 2016 to include the power to regulate the practice and procedure of public inquiries and fatal accident inquiries.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] As with other secondary legislation, an Act of Sederunt can only make law within the scope set out by an enabling act—an item of primary legislation from which power to make secondary legislation is derived.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] A non-exhaustive summary of these powers is provided below.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] In exercising these powers, the Court of Session can amend or repeal any enactment, including primary legislation, if it relates to matters an Act of Sederunt may cover.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] Note, however, that the power to regulate admission into the Faculty of Advocates is effectively delegated from the Court of Session to the Faculty, as the Court legislated to require that those seeking admission meet criteria set out by the Faculty.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] Rules for the functioning of the Court of Session are developed by the Scottish Civil Justice Council, which was established by the Scottish Civil Justice Council and Criminal Legal Assistance Act 2013.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The Council prepares draft rules of procedure for the civil courts and advises the Lord President on the development of the civil justice system in Scotland.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] The SCJC will consider changes to practice and procedure in response to policy initiatives, by specific request, or of its own accord.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] Membership of the council is provided for in the 2013 Act.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] Rules for the functioning of civil procedure in the sheriff courts are also prepared by the Scottish Civil Justice Council.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-sederunt] Acts of Sederunt, like other legislation in the United Kingdom, are introduced by enacting formulae.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The **Act of Settlement** (12 & 13 Will.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This had the effect of deposing the remaining descendants of Charles I other than Anne, as Sophia was the next Protestant in the line of succession.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Born into the House of Wittelsbach, Sophia was a granddaughter of James VI and I from his most junior surviving line, with the crowns descending only to her non-Catholic heirs.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Sophia predeceased Anne by two months, and her son succeeded to the throne as King George I, starting the Hanoverian dynasty in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] 1) had confirmed the independence of the Church of England from Roman Catholicism under the English monarch.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] One of the principal factors which contributed to the Glorious Revolution was the perceived assaults made on the Church of England by King James II, a Roman Catholic, who was deposed in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary II and her husband William III.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The need for this Act of Settlement was prompted by the death of Prince William, Duke of Gloucester, the son and heir of the future Queen Anne, and by the perceived threat posed by the pretensions to the throne by remaining Roman Catholic members of the House of Stuart.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The act played a key role in the formation of the Kingdom of Great Britain as, though England and Scotland had shared a monarch since 1603, they had remained separately governed countries, with the Act catalysing the Union of England and Scotland.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] However, the Parliament of Scotland was more reluctant to abandon the House of Stuart, members of which had been Scottish monarchs long before they became English.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Moreover, the Act also placed limits on both the role of foreigners in the British government and the power of the monarch with respect to the Parliament of England, though some of those provisions have been altered by subsequent legislation.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Along with the Bill of Rights 1689, the Act of Settlement remains today one of the main constitutional laws governing the succession not only to the throne of the United Kingdom, but to those of the other Commonwealth realms, whether by assumption or by patriation.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The Act of Settlement cannot be altered in any realm except by that realm's own parliament and, by convention, only with the consent of all the other realms, as it touches on the succession to the shared crown.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] On 26 March 2015, following the Perth Agreement, legislation amending the Act came into effect across the Commonwealth realms that removed the disqualification arising from marriage to a Roman Catholic and instituted absolute primogeniture.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The Bill of Rights also provided that the line of succession would go first through Mary's descendants, then through Mary's sister Anne and her descendants, and finally to the descendants of William III by a possible later marriage should he outlive Mary.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] During the debate, the House of Lords had attempted to append Sophia and her descendants to the line of succession, but the amendment failed in the Commons.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Mary II died childless in 1694, after which William III did not remarry.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] In 1700, Prince William, Duke of Gloucester, who was Anne's only child to survive infancy, died of what might have been smallpox at the age of 11.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Thus, Anne was left as the only person in line to the throne.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The Bill of Rights excluded Catholics from the throne, which ruled out James II and his children (as well as their descendants) sired after he converted to Catholicism in 1668.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] However, it did not provide for the further succession after Anne.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Parliament thus saw the need to settle the succession on Sophia and her descendants, and thereby guarantee the continuity of the Crown in the Protestant line.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] With religion and lineage initially decided, the ascendancy of William of Orange in 1689 would also bring his partiality to his Dutch favourites that followed.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] By 1701, anti-Dutch sentiment was widespread in England and action was considered necessary.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Thus, those who were Roman Catholics, and those who married Roman Catholics, were barred from ascending the throne.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Firstly, the monarch "shall join in communion with the Church of England".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This was intended to ensure the exclusion of a Roman Catholic monarch.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Along with James II's perceived despotism, his religion was the main cause of the Glorious Revolution, and of the previous linked religious and succession problems which had been resolved by the joint monarchy of William III and Mary II.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Second, if a person not native to England comes to the throne, England will not wage war for "any dominions or territories which do not belong to the Crown of England, without the consent of Parliament".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This would become relevant when a member of the House of Hanover ascended the British throne, as he would retain the territories of the Electorate of Hanover in what is now Lower Saxony (Germany), then part of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This provision has been dormant since Queen Victoria ascended the throne, because she did not inherit Hanover under the Salic Laws of the German-speaking states.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Third, no monarch may leave "the dominions of England, Scotland, or Ireland", without the consent of Parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This provision was repealed in 1716, at the request of George I who was also the Elector of Hanover and Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg within the Holy Roman Empire; because of this, and also for personal reasons, he wished to visit Hanover from time to time.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Fourth, all government matters within the jurisdiction of the Privy Council were to be transacted there, and all council resolutions were to be signed by those who advised and consented to them.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This was because Parliament wanted to know who was deciding policies, as sometimes councillors' signatures normally attached to resolutions were absent.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This provision was repealed early in Queen Anne's reign, as many councillors ceased to offer advice and some stopped attending meetings altogether.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] It has however been disapplied in particular cases by a number of other statutes.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Sixth, no person who has an office under the monarch, or receives a pension from the Crown, was to be a Member of Parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This provision was inserted to avoid unwelcome royal influence over the House of Commons.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] It remains in force, but with several exceptions; ministers of the Crown were exempted early on before Anne's death in order to continue some degree of royal patronage, but had to stand for a by-election to re-enter the House upon such appointment until 1926.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Seventh, judges' commissions are valid *quamdiu se bene gesserint* (during good behaviour) and if they do not behave themselves, they can be removed only by both Houses of Parliament (or in other Commonwealth realms the one House of Parliament, depending on the legislature's structure).
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This provision was the result of various monarchs influencing judges' decisions, and its purpose was to assure judicial independence.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This patent was used prior to 1701 but did not prevent Charles I from removing Sir John Walter as Chief Baron of the Exchequer.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Eighth, that "no Pardon under the Great Seal of England be pleadable to an Impeachment by the Commons in Parliament".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This meant in effect that no pardon by the monarch was to save someone from being impeached by the House of Commons.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The Tory administration that replaced the Whig Junto in 1699 took responsibility for steering the Act through Parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] As a result, it passed with little opposition, although five peers voted against it in the House of Lords, including the Earl of Huntingdon, his brother-in-law the Earl of Scarsdale and three others.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] While many shared their opposition to a "foreign" king, the general feeling was summed up as "better a German prince than a French one".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] For different reasons, various constitutionalists have praised the Act of Settlement: Henry Hallam called the Act "the seal of our constitutional laws" and David Lindsay Keir placed its importance above the Bill of Rights of 1689.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Naamani Tarkow wrote: "If one is to make sweeping statements, one may say that, save Magna Carta (more truly, its implications), the Act of Settlement is probably the most significant statute in English history".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The Act of Settlement was, in many ways, the major cause of the union of Scotland with England and Wales to form the Kingdom of Great Britain.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The Parliament of Scotland had not been consulted about the Act of Settlement, and, in response, passed the Act of Security 1704, through which Scotland reserved the right to choose its own successor to Queen Anne.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Stemming from this, the Parliament of England decided that, to ensure the stability and future prosperity of Great Britain, full union of the two parliaments and nations was essential before Anne's death.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] It used a combination of exclusionary legislation (the Alien Act 1705), politics, and bribery to achieve this within three years under the Act of Union 1707.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This success was in marked contrast to the four attempts at political union between 1606 and 1689, which all failed owing to a lack of political will in both kingdoms.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] By virtue of Article II of the Treaty of Union, which defined the succession to the throne of Great Britain, the Act of Settlement became part of Scots law as well.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] In addition to excluding James II, who died a few months after the act received royal assent, and his Roman Catholic children, Prince James (*The Old Pretender*) and the Princess Royal, the Act also excluded the descendants of Princess Henrietta, the youngest sister of James II.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Henrietta's only child with surviving issue was Anne, Queen of Sardinia, a Roman Catholic, from whom descend all Jacobite pretenders after 1807.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Elizabeth had borne nine children who reached adulthood, of whom Sophia was the youngest daughter.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] He was restored to the line of succession in 2015 when the Succession to the Crown Act 2013 came into force, and became 34th in line.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The next most senior living descendant of the Electress Sophia who had been ineligible to succeed on this ground is George Windsor, Earl of St Andrews, the elder son of Prince Edward, Duke of Kent, who married the Roman Catholic Sylvana Palma Tomaselli in 1988.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] His son, Lord Downpatrick, converted to Roman Catholicism in 2003 and is the most senior descendant of Sophia to be barred as a result of his religion.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] In 2008 his daughter, Lady Marina Windsor, also converted to Catholicism and was removed from the line of succession.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] More recently, Peter Phillips, the son of Anne, Princess Royal, and eleventh in line to the throne, married Autumn Kelly; Kelly had been brought up as a Roman Catholic, but she converted to Anglicanism prior to the wedding.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Had she not done so, Phillips would have forfeited his place in the succession upon their marriage, only to have it restored in 2015.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] As well as being part of the law of the United Kingdom, the Act of Settlement was received into the laws of all the countries and territories over which the British monarch reigned.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] It remains part of the laws of the 15 Commonwealth realms and the relevant jurisdictions within those realms.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The Succession to the Crown Act 2013 changed many provisions of this Act.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Challenges have been made against the Act of Settlement, especially its provisions regarding Roman Catholics and preference for males.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] However, changing the act is a complex process, since the act governs the shared succession of all the Commonwealth realms.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The Statute of Westminster 1931 acknowledges by established convention that any changes to the rules of succession may be made only with the agreement of all of the states involved, with concurrent amendments to be made by each state's parliament or parliaments.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Further, as the current monarch's eldest child and, in turn, his eldest child, are Anglican males, any change to the succession laws would have no immediate implications.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Consequently, there was little public concern with the issues and debate had been confined largely to academic circles until the November 2010 announcement that Prince William was to marry.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This raised the question of what would happen if he were to produce first a daughter and then a son.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] In October 2011 the Australian federal government was reported to have reached an agreement with all of the states on potential changes to their laws in the wake of amendments to the Act of Settlement.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The practice of the Australian states—for example, New South Wales and Victoria—has been, when legislating to repeal some imperial statutes so far as they still applied in Australia, to provide that imperial statutes concerning the royal succession remain in force.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The legal process required at the federal level remains, theoretically, unclear.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The Australian constitution, as was noted during the crisis of 1936, contains no power for the federal parliament to legislate with respect to the monarchy.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Anne Twomey reviews three possible interpretations of the clause.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] However, Twomey expresses confidence that, if the High Court of Australia were to be faced with the problems of covering clause 2, it would find some way to conclude that, with regard to Australia, the clause is subject solely to Australian law.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This, he claimed, discriminated against non-Anglicans, including Catholics, who are the largest faith group in Canada.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] In 2002, O'Donohue launched a court action that argued the Act of Settlement violated the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*, but, the case was dismissed by the court.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] It found that, as the Act of Settlement is part of the Canadian constitution, the Charter of Rights and Freedoms, as another part of the same constitution, does not have supremacy over it.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] An appeal of the decision was dismissed on 16 March 2005.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Some commentators state that, as a result of this, any single provincial legislature could hinder any attempts to change this Act, and by extension, to the line of succession for the shared crown of all 16 Commonwealth realms.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Others contend that that is not the case, and changes to the succession instituted by an Act of the Parliament of Canada "[in accord] with the convention of symmetry that preserves the personal unity of the British and Dominion Crowns".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] With the announcement in 2007 of the engagement of Peter Phillips to Autumn Kelly, a Roman Catholic and a Canadian, discussion about the Act of Settlement was revived.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] (In fact, Lord St Andrews had already lost his place in the line of succession when he married the Roman Catholic Canadian Sylvana Palma Tomaselli in 1988.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] From time to time there has been debate over repealing the clause that prevents Roman Catholics, or those who marry one, from ascending to the British throne.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Proponents of repeal argue that the clause is a bigoted anachronism; Cardinal Winning, who was leader of the Roman Catholic Church in Scotland, called the act an "insult" to Catholics.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] They also note that the monarch must swear to defend the faith and be a member of the Anglican Communion, but that a Roman Catholic monarch would, like all Roman Catholics, owe allegiance to the Pope.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] This would, according to opponents of repeal, amount to a loss of sovereignty for the Anglican Church.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] When in December 1978 there was media speculation that Prince Charles might marry a Roman Catholic, Powell defended the provision that excludes Roman Catholics from ascending the throne, stating his objection was not rooted in religious bigotry but in political considerations.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] He said a Roman Catholic monarch would mean the acceptance of a source of authority external to the realm and "in the literal sense, foreign to the Crown-in-Parliament ...
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The Scottish Parliament unanimously passed a motion in 1999 calling for the complete removal of any discrimination linked to the monarchy and the repeal of the Act of Settlement.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] As the Convention nowhere lists the right to succeed to the Crown as a human right, the challenge was rejected.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] *The Guardian* subsequently launched a campaign to repeal the Act, which by the end of May 2002 received signatures from 72 MPs, 35 peers, the Archbishop of York David Hope and several non-Anglican religious leaders.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] In December 2004, a private member's bill—the Succession to the Crown Bill—was introduced in the House of Lords.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The government, headed by Tony Blair, blocked all attempts to revise the succession laws, claiming it would raise too many constitutional issues and it was unnecessary at the time.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] In the British general election the following year, Michael Howard promised to work towards having the prohibition removed if the Conservative Party gained a majority of seats in the House of Commons, but the election was won by Blair's Labour Party.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Four years later, plans drawn up by Chris Bryant were revealed that would end the exclusion of Catholics from the throne and end the doctrine of male-preference primogeniture in favour of absolute primogeniture, which governs succession solely on birth order and not on sex.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The issue was raised again in January 2009, when a private member's bill to amend the Act of Succession was introduced in parliament.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Stephenson King, Prime Minister of Saint Lucia, said he supported the idea and it was reported that the government of New Zealand did, as well.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Later the same year, the Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, Nick Clegg, announced that the government was considering a change in the law.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] Cameron reportedly also proposed removing the restriction on successors being or marrying Roman Catholics; however, potential Roman Catholic successors would be required to convert to Anglicanism prior to acceding to the throne.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] In reaction to the letter and media coverage, Harper stated that, this time, he was "supportive" of what he saw as "reasonable modernizations".
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] At the 2011 Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting on 28 October 2011, the prime ministers of the other Commonwealth realms agreed to support Cameron's proposed changes to the Act.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The bill put before the Parliament of the United Kingdom would act as a model for the legislation required to be passed in at least some of the other realms, and any changes would only first take effect if the Duke of Cambridge were to have a daughter before a son.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The British group Republic asserted that succession reform would not make the monarchy any less discriminatory.
[src:accession-declaration-act-1910/act-of-settlement-1701] The disqualification arising from marriage to a Roman Catholic was removed by the Succession to the Crown Act 2013.
